         <h1>Adam Ulam, a Top Historian Of Soviet Union, Dies at 77 </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Adam B. Ulam , a Harvard historian known for his shrewd understanding of the inner workings of the Soviet Union , particularly at the time of Lenin and Stalin , died on Tuesday in a hospital in Cambridge , Mass . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 77 . <br><blue>3</blue>The cause was lung cancer , his family said . <br><blue>4</blue>In the days before he died , he was revising , from his hospital bed , the autobiography he planned to publish on the Internet . <br><blue>5</blue>The first chapter is available at www.aulam.org . <br><blue>6</blue>Dr. Ulam traveled to Russia just once , for a brief trip in the mid-1980 's , as Mikhail S. Gorbachev was beginning the reforms that would result in the collapse of the Soviet Union . <br><blue>7</blue>An immigrant from Poland , Dr. Ulam often joked that he preferred '' overdeveloped countries '' with good food and comfortable beds . <br><blue>8</blue>Yet his encyclopedic knowledge of the Soviet system -- from the roots of the Bolshevik Revolution in 19th-century Russia , to Stalin 's strategies for terror , to arcane details of Politburo procedure -- was regarded by Harvard colleagues as without peer , especially in the 1960 's and 1970 's . <br><blue>9</blue>Lacking any access to the Soviet archives , which were opened after he had written all but one of his 18 books , Dr. Ulam informed himself through voracious reading of newspapers , journals and memoirs and by panning scholarly gold out of the vast and numbingly dull official literature of Communism . <br><blue>10</blue>The book for which Dr. Ulam is best known is '' Stalin : The Man and His Era '' ( Viking , 1973 ) . <br><blue>11</blue>It showed how the not-especially-smart son of a Georgian cobbler , who was scorned by Trotsky as '' the most eminent mediocrity in the party , '' consolidated power and how he used it with genocidal fury . <br><blue>12</blue>In a review in The New York Times , the historian Paul Avrich described the book as '' the fullest and most up-to-date biography of Stalin now available . '' <br><blue>13</blue>An earlier book by Dr. Ulam , '' The Bolsheviks '' ( Macmillan , 1965 ) , was praised in a Times review by Henry L. Roberts as '' the most rewarding single study of Lenin that I have encountered . '' '' <br><blue>14</blue>The really impressive feature of Ulam 's book is that he is thinking hard all the way , '' Mr. Roberts wrote , adding that his '' intellectual seriousness is a great relief and pleasure . '' <br><blue>15</blue>Dr. Ulam was known at Harvard as a man who did not take himself or his work all that seriously . <br><blue>16</blue>When Nikita Khrushchev was unexpectedly purged in 1964 , Dr. Ulam was asked why he had n't predicted it . '' <br><blue>17</blue>If it came as a surprise to Khrushchev , why would n't it come as a surprise to me ? '' <br><blue>18</blue>he replied . <br><blue>19</blue>Dr. Ulam dressed haphazardly , often wearing a jacket from a blue suit with pants from a brown suit to Harvard 's Russian Research Center , where he was the director throughout most of the 1970 's and 1980 's . <br><blue>20</blue>Nearly every morning -- and he often worked seven days a week -- he went to the coffee room at the center at Harvard and visited with colleagues and students for an hour or so . <br><hr><br><blue>1(4)</blue>: <m_str>Stalin</m_str> (10_12) 	<m_str>Stalin</m_str> (12_26) 	<m_str>Stalin</m_str> (1_29) 	<m_str>Stalin 's</m_str> (8_22) 	<br><blue>2(2)</blue>: <m_str>the mid-1980 's</m_str> (6_14) 	<m_str>The first chapter</m_str> (5_1) 	<br><blue>3(2)</blue>: <m_str>I</m_str> (13_38) 	<m_str>me</m_str> (17_19) 	<br><blue>4(2)</blue>: <m_str>the Soviet Union</m_str> (1_18) 	<m_str>the Soviet Union</m_str> (6_33) 	<br><blue>5(5)</blue>: <m_str>it</m_str> (16_19) 	<m_str>it</m_str> (17_2) 	<m_str>Ulam 's book</m_str> (14_6) 	<m_str>the book</m_str> (12_15) 	<m_str>it</m_str> (17_13) 	<br><blue>6(37)</blue>: <m_str>Dr. Ulam</m_str> (15_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (7_11) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (1